[3] Philippines (Cordillera region)
Date: Fri 13 Sep 2013
Source: Baguio Midland Courier [edited]
http://baguiomidlandcourier.com.ph/health.asp?mode=archives/2013/september/9-8-2013/health1.txt


The regional Department of Health reported 902 patients were admitted to various hospitals in the Cordillera [region] due to suspected chikungunya although no cases of death were recorded since the start of the year [2013].

Records from the DOH Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit show that from the 902 cases, the health agency was able to send 151 blood specimens to the Research Institute for Tropical Medicine and only 44 were confirmed positive for chikungunya [virus infection].

From the confirmed cases, Ifugao topped with 18, followed by Mountain Province with 10, Kalinga and Apayao with 6 each, while 2 cases were from Baguio.

One confirmed case was recorded in Abra, while the remaining case is a patient from outside the region.

The World Health Organization defines chikungunya fever as a viral illness transmitted through the bite of infected _Aedes_ mosquitoes. As it usually co-occurs with and resembles dengue, the chikungunya fever is often misdiagnosed.

DOH-RESU reported that the ages of people who showed signs and symptoms of chikungunya range from 3 months old to 92 years old with 25 as the median age.

The most common signs and symptoms of the recorded cases are fever, rashes, arthralgia [joint pain], arthritis, myalgia [muscle pain], headache, back pain, red eyes, cough, and coryza [cold symptoms].

DOH earlier declared an outbreak of chikungunya fever cases, which is caused by dengue-carrying mosquitoes, in Lamut, Ifugao after more than 500 persons contracted the illness.

DOH Officer-in-charge Veleriano Lopez said the regional health agency together with the various provincial health offices have been facilitating the sending of blood samples to the Research Institute for Tropical Medicine for confirmation.

DOH is also encouraging the conduct of active case detection and prompt reporting of cases while providing assistance to local government units with reported cases of chikungunya.

The agency, through its RESU personnel, also oriented representatives of municipal health offices and public health nurses about the illness.

Concerned LGUs are also being asked to implement anti-dengue drive like the 4 o'clock habit and promote clean surroundings.

[Byline: Harley F. Palangchao]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There have been chikungunya virus outbreaks in various parts of the Philippines this year (2013). This outbreak in the Cordillera region is one of the larger ones. But with only 44 of 151 samples testing positive for chikungunya virus infection, one wonders what the etiologies of the discarded cases might have been (perhaps dengue virus infections in some instances).

A map showing the location of the Philippines can be accessed at http://www.mapsofworld.com/philippines/maps/Philippines-Location.jpg. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/1pq_. - Mod.TY]
